metadata.name: Uninhabitable #172
metadata.description:
Uninhabitable is a generative system built only from ellipses. The process of playing with different geometric and trigonometric disruptions gives rise to four different compositions which seek to evoque living constructions and environments. Besides the shape itself and its related distortion, the stroke weight of the lines plays a meaningful role in the piece. Following a discrete range [0.01,0.1,1] the weight reveals the process allowing the viewer to realize the trace of the huge amount of lines in each piece. This back and forth between scales and context is, while kind of stripping the code, part of my continuing interest on understanding the -usually- crazy paths of machines' way of thinking.

Press "h" to see it and high resolution and refresh to get back to the initial state. Press "h" to save it.

Uninhabitable is an original work by Iskra Velitchkova. 2021.

metadata.name: Poem Of Atoms #17
metadata.description:
There is a force in the universe that binds everything together
It's a electronic web that connects everything in a delicate balance. 
Some call it fate. But few know the truth.
They are the lifeblood of our society, and they are what keep us moving forward. We are constantly surrounded by them, and they are always changing. It's not a force, it's an orbit. And the dots are the energy sources.

Made with P5js

metadata.name: abstraction #93
metadata.description:
Diagrams of patterns on spheres, planets, fields, and platonic solids rendered isometrically. Ink on paper (on js).

Press DOWN to save an SVG suitable for plotting (or laser etching).
Press UP to save a 2400 x 2400 png. If you need a bigger image, zoom out and refresh, the canvas will fit the window.

Physics is fundamentally idealist. We search for simple rules from which the complexities of the universe emerge. But real systems are exceptionally complex, closed-form solutions are the exception. The deeper we dive into the fundamental nature of the universe, the less clear the rules become. Are the rules we've developed fundamental, or are they empirical approximations?

metadata.name: Ethereal Microcosm #179
metadata.description:
An exploration of algorithmic organisms in a contained environment.

This piece is about the simulation of microscopic patterns using a high number of even tinier agents all following the same rules. Different species evolve and interact together, resulting in stabilizing patterns out of their parametric configurations. A form of artificial life.

This work is based on the paper "Characteristics of pattern formation and evolution in approximations of physarum transport networks", written by Jeff Jones and popularized in the artistic field by Sage Jenson. Some features were added to increase the visual and behavioral complexity of the system. Agents are divided into different species, with their own set of rules and interacting with their own substrate. Substrates also interact with each other and agents will mutate in contact of some of them.

NFT License
Runs properly on Chrome 97.0.4692.99
GPU intensive

Press P to pause (double tab touch devices)

metadata.name: GRAPHEME #97
metadata.description:
Released on the occasion of the Tribute to Herbert W. Franke. 
www.tribute-hwf.com

“One criterion for art involves the process used by the artist for shaping the work. In the special case of mathematically supported fine art, the artmaking process occurs in a mathematically defined operation that allows the generation and transformation of images, methods used for picture processing.” - Herbert W. Franke

I first came across Franke’s ‘Ornamental Alphabets’ in his book 𝘊𝘰𝘮𝘱𝘶𝘵𝘦𝘳 𝘎𝘳𝘢𝘱𝘩𝘪𝘤𝘴 - 𝘊𝘰𝘮𝘱𝘶𝘵𝘦𝘳 𝘈𝘳𝘵, and was intrigued with the idea of using a simple letterform to explore different generative image processing techniques. 

I’ve used letters and writing in my work for a long time, both with letterpress printing and in my asemic poetry programs. With asemic writing, I generate unrecognizable letters to reference text, and here I use recognizable letterforms removed from their typical function as language signifiers. 

My goal with this project was to build as much texture and layering as possible by warping and collaging the letters together in various ways. The font I’m using is a design I made years ago to supplement my wood type collection for printing. I really enjoyed being able to bring that part of my past work into my generative art practice. 

Each image is composed of the letters found in the hash for that piece, divided into either vowels or consonants. The program builds on a technique I’ve used before, where I generate an image to an off-screen canvas and then dive through the pixels to pull out the color and form I want to surface in the final image.

25% of the primary sales will be donated on-chain to the Foundation Herbert W. Franke. These funds will be used by ZKM Karlsruhe to digitize Franke’s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. Any additional funds raised will be donated to the Rütgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.

- Press “R” to increase the pixel density and reload the image (this can be render intensive and will create a really large file suitable for printing)
- Press “S” to save a copy

Made with p5js
Artist: Sarah Ridgley
October, 2022

metadata.name: Handachak #116
metadata.description:
I have always been looking for solutions that can connect different visual elements in such a way as to create an integrated system and structure and each part of the work plays its own role in this system.
Another point is that always attributing physical characteristics to abstract forms creates aesthetic qualities. From a general point of view, one of these features is perspective, and in this project we see a type of perspective in an abstract and geometric structure.
"Handachak" means "Geometry" in ancient Persian.

metadata.name: Rhythmic Contrast #29
metadata.description:
Ever since I was a student I have been fascinated by the relationship between rhythm and contrast and my work explores that relationship. Rhythmic Contrast is a pattern of regular or irregular pulses which happen in color, shape, tension, direction, texture and space. Rhythmic Contrast is a pattern of sound and silence.
Thank you.

metadata.name: fx(ornament) 2022 #188
metadata.description:
Tis the season to celebrate and what better way than with a collectible series of 2022 generative ornaments. Perfect for yourself or as gifts for people you love. 

Designed to be printed or plotted and then cut out and hung on your tree or any other place that needs a little festive cheer. 

I’ll be picking a few of my favorite outputs and sending the token owners special limited edition signed laser cut versions of their ornaments. 

———————

LIVE MODE FEATURES
- L prepares it for plotting or cutting
- S exports a layered SVG
- P exports a PNG
- 1-9 plays with color combos

———————

For years my family has collected Wallace Silver Candy Cane ornaments. Each Christmas the kids open up that years design and add it to the tree. With my daughters mostly grown, we now have quite the collection of dozens of ornaments from all the years. Each one full with memories and emotions. 

This series is inspired by that tradition, starting with 2022, and continuing with a new release each year. I hope you enjoy this series and it brings much delight and joy to you, your family, and friends this holiday season.

metadata.name: strokes-1 #26
metadata.description:
A generative abstract painting using layers of strokes of different size, strength and color.

The painting is rendered by simulating one stroke at a time. The recipe is similar for all paintings. First, wide faint brush strokes cover the canvas with a background texture, then a few strong brush strokes give the piece some character. After that, very fine rapid strokes give the piece some interesting detail and finally, dabs of very short brush strokes are applied for additional sense of depth. 

The rendering takes some time. With large screen sizes, you get bigger pictures (for printing!), but the rendering is slower. 

Once the work is painted, you can hit 's' to save a png file. 

There are 7 different colour schemes.

metadata.name: Flow #18
metadata.description:
Flow is a collection of animations based on noise fields and fluid dynamics. The pieces are designed to run continuously, and they produce slowly evolving images that seem to drip, swirl, pulse, and flow. Dense networks of patterns emerge and decay as the pieces evolve. Because of their subtle movement, these pieces make excellent wall art when run on a display monitor.

The algorithm is sensitive to canvas size and will animate differently depending on the size of the window in which it is running. Optimal viewing size is at a resolution of at least 1,000 x 1,000 pixels, while smaller animations will tend to flow faster, develop fewer eddies, and build more simplistic patterns. In this way, each iteration represents not just a single animation, but a large number of closely related animations that can be explored. To see the exact same animation, you must run it at the exact same size. 

-spacebar will pause the animation

-return will resume the animation

-r will restart the animation

-s will allow you to save a still capture

Flow, 2022
-hieroglyphica
